olving environment. After surveying the development of hand combat traditions in Guangdong Province from roughly the start of the nineteenth century until 1949, the authors turn to Wing Chun, noting its development, the changing social attitudes towards this practice over time, and its ultimate emergence as a global art form.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aKung fuxChinaxChina. 0aKung fuzChina. 0aMartial artsxChina. 0aMartial artszChina. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Cultural Anthropology. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aSociology : Sports and Society. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Martial Arts & Self-Defense.2bisacsh1 aNielson, Jon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438456959423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438456959/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles